notesStmt.note: Some gold has flaked and silver paint has oxidized on fols. 19r, 57r, 98r, 105r; some of the blue rubrics throughout are now faint; paint has been worn/flaked on fol. 69r, rendering the faces in the miniature blank
Some of the miniature appear to have been retouched

Inscriptions in miniatures: fol. 19r: illegible inscriptions on intertwined gold and silver vine scrolls in right margin; fol. 45r: illegible inscriptions on the Angel Gabriel's scroll, and on open book in front of the Virgin Mary; in the lower margin is the inscription: "Qui bien en ionesse naprent en sa veillesse sen repant"; fol. 57r: illegible inscriptions written on gold and silver scrolls in lower margin; fol. 75v: the angel in heaven holds a scroll that reads: "Gloria in excelsis deo"; fol. 98r: illegible inscriptions (pseudo-Greek letters?) on gold and silver scrolls in margins; fol. 105r: illegible inscriptions on gold scrolls in right margin
Incipit text at the beginning of each major textual division is gilded
Calendar and prayers on fols. 19r-24v and 25r-28v in French
De Ricci, Seymour, with the assistance of W. J. Wilson, Census of Medieval and Renaissance Manuscripts in the United States and Canada, vol. 2 (New York,: H. W. Wilson, 1935-40), p. 2035, no. 63.

msIdentifier.collection: John Frederick Lewis Collection of European Manuscripts

msContents.summary: This Book of Hours of the Use of Paris was perhaps produced in Brittany, as the style of the fourteen large miniatures and contents of the calendar and litany suggest. The miniatures in the Hours of the Virgin for Sext, (Flight into Egypt, fol. 80v), None (Adoration of the Magi, fol. 85v), and Vespers (Presentation in the Temple, fol. 90v) diverge from the traditional iconographic sequence. Several of the foliate borders surrounding the miniatures contain Greek-inspired pseudo script.

binding.p: French red morocco, triple gilt fillets around sides and gilt frames in centers with floral ornaments at the corners, elaborately floral gilt back, gilt edges, seventeenth century

origin.p: Inclusion of Saints Yvo, Brioc and Corentine in the Litany (fol. 121r) may indicate that the manuscript was made for use in Brittany; first half of the 15th century

history.provenance: Unidentified coat of arms of the original owner in the lower margin of fol. 80v, three doves proper on a field of gules; Bull and Auvache, London, ₤30 (as per inscription in J.F. Lewis' hand on one of the back flyleaves); John Frederick Lewis, Philadelphia (bookplate); given by his widow, Anne Baker Lewis, to the Free Library of Philadelphia in 1936
